<!-- ═══ PHILOSOPHY ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page" id="page-philosophy">
  <h2>Engineering Philosophy</h2>
  <p style="max-width:640px;margin-bottom:28px">The systems I find interesting are the ones where a wrong assumption early creates a problem that's expensive to fix later. These are the principles I apply to avoid that.</p>
  <div class="phil-grid">
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Prompts are API contracts</div><div class="pcell-text">In LLM applications, prompt structure is the most consequential engineering decision. An unspecified output schema means every downstream parser is a bug waiting to happen. I design prompts with the same rigour I'd use for an API interface — specifying types, formats, and failure modes explicitly.</div></div>
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Security in the pipeline, not after it</div><div class="pcell-text">Vulnerability scanning as a post-deploy audit catches problems after they're already in production. Integrating it as a blocking CI stage catches them before anything ships. The DevSecOps pipeline project is the practical demonstration of this principle, not a theoretical one.</div></div>
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Schema design is architecture</div><div class="pcell-text">The booking system taught me this concretely. Database schema decisions made early — how to model slot availability, how to structure the bookings collection — determined whether real-time synchronisation was even possible later. Data model choices are architectural choices.</div></div>
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Build for the next reader</div><div class="pcell-text">Documentation and naming aren't ceremony — they're the mechanism by which you hand work off without a synchronous meeting. Clear code is faster code, because onboarding costs time that didn't have to be spent.</div></div>
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Automate the repetitive, think on the novel</div><div class="pcell-text">Anything that runs the same way every time should be scripted. CI/CD, testing, environment setup — automating the repeatable parts creates capacity to focus on the problems that actually require judgement.</div></div>
    <div class="pcell"><div class="pcell-title">Know what you don't know</div><div class="pcell-text">The learning journey section of this platform is deliberately honest. Conflating familiarity with expertise is a failure mode I work to avoid — both when representing my own skills and when scoping technical work. Honest self-assessment makes collaboration faster for everyone involved.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

