      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Request Flow</span>\n\n<span class="ac3">POST /analyze</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">FastAPI Layer</span>          <span class="ac4">← auth, schema validation</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Preprocessor</span>           <span class="ac4">← normalise text, manage length</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Prompt Constructor</span>     <span class="ac4">← structured prompt + output schema</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">LLM Inference</span>          <span class="ac4">← credibility reasoning + evidence</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Response Parser</span>        <span class="ac4">← JSON extraction, schema enforcement</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">DB Write + Response</span>    <span class="ac4">← stored, structured JSON returned</span>`,
      dec:'Enforcing a strict output schema *inside* the prompt fixed the consistency problem. Without it, LLM responses vary in format across calls — making every downstream parser brittle. Prompt design treated as API contract design.',
      dec2:'MongoDB over SQL: analysis results have variable structure (different articles produce different evidence structures). Flexible document storage avoided constant schema migrations for output variability.',
      challenges:['Consistent parseable JSON from the LLM required prompt iteration and fallback parsing — not just instruction-following.','Mid-inference API failures needed retry logic and graceful degradation.','Response quality varied by article length — chunking strategy required for longer content.'],
      testing:'Manual testing against known credible and non-credible articles. Postman API endpoint testing. Edge cases: empty input, oversized content, special characters. Error path testing for LLM timeout and malformed response scenarios.',
      lessons:'Prompt versions need tracking as carefully as code versions. I now treat prompt changes as commits with rationale, not edits.',
      future:'Multi-source verification · Confidence visualisation · Citation support · User feedback loop · Analytics dashboard'}},
  {id:'p2',tags:['ai','backend'],name:'AI Interview Coach',desc:'Adaptive platform generating role-specific interview questions with LLM-powered feedback on user responses — stateless, multi-turn design.',focus:'Adaptive AI Workflow',fc:'f-arch',
   stack:['Python','FastAPI','LLM APIs','Prompt Engineering','Docker'],
   d:{summary:'Static question banks don\'t adapt to what a candidate says. This system generates role-specific questions and evaluates actual user responses with LLM inference — not a generic checklist. The design challenge: reusable prompt templates across technical and behavioural formats without forking the codebase.',
      problem:'Traditional tools can\'t evaluate a specific answer against a specific question with contextual feedback. Real-time adaptive feedback requires stateless multi-turn design that scales horizontally.',
      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Session Flow</span>\n\n<span class="ac3">POST /session/start</span>   <span class="ac4">← interview type + target role</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Question Generator</span>    <span class="ac4">← LLM + role-specific template</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac3">POST /answer</span>          <span class="ac4">← response + session context in body</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Evaluation Engine</span>     <span class="ac4">← LLM scores answer vs question + role</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Feedback Formatter</span>    <span class="ac4">← structured: strengths, gaps, suggestions</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac3">200 {feedback, score}</span>`,
      dec:'Stateless API design: passing conversation history in each request body rather than server-side sessions means any instance handles any request. No sticky sessions, easier horizontal scaling, simpler local testing.',
      dec2:'One codebase for both interview types via a mode parameter. Shared prompt templates with type-specific injections — improvements to evaluation quality benefit both modes simultaneously.',
      challenges:['Reusable templates performing well across very different interview types required systematic comparison of prompt structures.','Session context encoding: fitting enough prior conversation into each call without exceeding token limits.'],
      testing:'Prompt evaluation: compared output quality across versions for identical question/answer pairs. Postman endpoint testing. Edge cases: very short answers, off-topic responses.',
      lessons:'Stateless conversation design is the right default for this class of application. Context-in-request is simpler to reason about, test, and scale than server-managed session state.',
      future:'Voice-based interviews · Resume-aware question generation · Coding interview with sandboxed execution · Performance analytics'}},
  {id:'p3',tags:['ai','backend'],name:'RAG-Based Research Assistant',desc:'Document Q&A using retrieval-augmented generation — answers grounded in uploaded documents, not model memory.',focus:'Retrieval · Context Engineering',fc:'f-ai',
   stack:['Python','FastAPI','RAG','Vector Search','LLM APIs'],
   d:{summary:'LLMs hallucinate on documents they haven\'t seen. This system builds a retrieval layer between the user\'s question and the LLM — only the most relevant document chunks are passed to the model at inference time.',
      problem:'Full-document context exceeds limits for long documents and is expensive. Open-ended generation without grounding produces hallucinations. Retrieval narrows context to what\'s relevant before generating.',
      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Ingestion</span>\n<span class="ac3">Document Upload</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Text Extraction + Chunking</span>   <span class="ac4">← sentence-aware, overlap control</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Embedding + Vector Index</span>     <span class="ac4">← persisted for retrieval</span>\n\n<span class="ac4">  Query</span>\n<span class="ac3">POST /ask {question}</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Query Embed + Similarity Search</span>  <span class="ac4">← top-k chunks</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Prompt Assembly</span>       <span class="ac4">← question + retrieved context</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">LLM Answer Generation</span> <span class="ac4">← grounded in document content</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac3">200 {answer, source_chunks}</span>`,
      dec:'RAG over fine-tuning: fine-tuning is expensive, requires retraining for each new corpus, and still hallucinates outside training distribution. RAG works with any new document without retraining, and retrieved chunks provide an explicit audit trail.',
      dec2:'Chunking strategy is the most consequential implementation decision. Chunk size and overlap directly affect retrieval quality — too small loses context, too large dilutes relevance. Required iteration across document types.',
      challenges:['Parsing varied file formats while preserving semantic structure.','Tuning chunk size and overlap for different document types took significant experimentation.','Prompt construction using retrieved context without exceeding token budgets.'],
      testing:'Retrieval quality: compared retrieved chunks against manually identified relevant sections for test questions. Answer quality on documents with known ground truth. Edge cases: ambiguous queries, no matching content, very long documents.',
      lessons:'The chunking decision matters more than the LLM choice. Poor chunking produces poor retrieval regardless of model quality.',
      future:'Multi-document support · Source citation · Better retrieval ranking · Enterprise document management'}},
  {id:'p4',tags:['backend'],name:'Real-Time Expert Booking System',desc:'Concurrent-safe scheduling backend — prevents double-booking under load via atomic DB operations and WebSocket availability sync.',focus:'Backend Architecture',fc:'f-backend',
   stack:['Python','FastAPI','Socket.IO','MongoDB'],
   d:{summary:'Booking systems fail silently when two users try to reserve the same slot simultaneously. This project focused on the concurrency problem: keeping availability state consistent across concurrent requests through real-time synchronisation.',
      problem:'Multiple users can query the same expert simultaneously. Without synchronisation, both can see a slot as available and book it — a double-booking conflict. The challenge: prevent this at the DB level while notifying all connected clients of state changes immediately.',
      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Concurrent Request Handling</span>\n\n<span class="ac3">Client A + Client B</span>     <span class="ac4">← both query availability</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac3">GET /experts/:id/availability</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">FastAPI → MongoDB</span>       <span class="ac4">← read open slots</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac3">Client A: POST /bookings</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Atomic findOneAndUpdate</span>  <span class="ac4">← find + reserve in single transaction</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Socket.IO broadcast</span>      <span class="ac4">← push updated state to ALL clients</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Client B sees slot gone</span>  <span class="ac4">← without polling or refreshing</span>`,
      dec:'Socket.IO over polling: polling introduces latency (stale views between intervals) and server load proportional to connected clients. Push means clients see changes instantly, and the server only sends data when state actually changes.',
      dec2:'MongoDB\'s atomic findOneAndUpdate allowed slot reservation and status update in one operation without explicit locking — sufficient for this concurrency pattern.',
      challenges:['Ensuring all connected clients see the same availability state without race conditions.','Database consistency under concurrent booking requests.','Clean API contract separation between availability queries and booking operations.'],
      testing:'Concurrent booking simulation: simultaneous requests for the same slot to verify atomic operations prevented double-booking. WebSocket propagation testing. Auth flow testing. Postman API contract testing.',
      lessons:'Schema design is architecture. How I modelled slot availability in MongoDB determined whether atomic booking was even possible. Data model decisions made early have long consequences.',
      future:'Payment integration · Video consultation · Calendar sync · Analytics dashboard'}},
  {id:'p5',tags:['devops','cloud'],name:'Cloud-Based Secure DevOps Pipeline',desc:'CI/CD with vulnerability scanning as a blocking deployment gate — critical findings stop the pipeline, not just trigger an alert.',focus:'DevSecOps · CI/CD',fc:'f-devops',
   stack:['Docker','GitHub Actions','AWS','Python','Linux'],
   d:{summary:'Manual deployment is slow and skips security checks under pressure. This pipeline automates build, test, containerisation, security scanning, and cloud deployment — with security integrated as a delivery gate, not a post-deploy audit.',
      problem:'Traditional CI/CD treats security as an afterthought. Scan results arrive after code is already deployed, creating a window where vulnerable code is in production while the team responds to alerts. DevSecOps closes that window.',
      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Pipeline Stages (GitHub Actions)</span>\n\n<span class="ac3">git push → trigger</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Static Analysis</span>         <span class="ac4">← code quality, dependency audit</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Unit Test Suite</span>         <span class="ac4">← fail fast on regressions</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Docker Build</span>            <span class="ac4">← reproducible container image</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Vulnerability Scan</span>      <span class="ac4">← BLOCKING: critical findings halt deploy</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Registry Push</span>           <span class="ac4">← versioned, tagged image</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">AWS Deployment</span>          <span class="ac4">← target environment</span>\n<span class="ac2">  ↓</span>\n<span class="ac1">Health Check</span>            <span class="ac4">← confirms live before marking success</span>`,
      dec:'Scanning is a *blocking* stage, not informational. An informational scan relies on a human to read and act on alerts under pressure. A blocking stage removes that decision point — nothing ships with a critical finding.',
      dec2:'GitHub Actions over Jenkins: zero infrastructure overhead at this scale, native GitHub integration for PR-level feedback, marketplace ecosystem for security scanning tools.',
      challenges:['Tuning severity thresholds to block on critical/high findings without creating alert fatigue from low-severity noise.','Health check design: defining what "healthy" means for the deployed service and timeout before declaring failure.'],
      testing:'End-to-end pipeline tested against code with known vulnerabilities to confirm blocking behaviour. Health check tested with healthy and degraded service states.',
      lessons:'DevSecOps is a culture change before it\'s a tooling change. The pipeline only works if the team treats a blocking security stage as a feature, not friction.',
      future:'Kubernetes deployment target · Terraform IaC · Prometheus + Grafana · Automated rollback · SBOM generation'}},
  {id:'p6',tags:['cloud'],name:'AWS Event-Driven Pipeline',desc:'Serverless event processing — compute runs only when events occur, infrastructure provisioned as code via Terraform.',focus:'Serverless · Cloud Architecture',fc:'f-cloud',
   stack:['AWS Lambda','S3','CloudWatch','Terraform','Python'],
   d:{summary:'When applications need to respond to file uploads or scheduled events, keeping a server running to wait is wasteful. This pipeline implements serverless event-driven processing where compute only runs when there\'s work to do.',
      problem:'Server-based processing pays for compute during idle periods — which for event-driven workloads can be most of the time. Serverless removes idle cost and scales automatically. The engineering challenge: designing for stateless function execution.',
      arch:`<span class="ac4">  Event Sources → Processing → Storage</span>\n\n<span class="ac3">S3 Object Upload</span>       ──┐\n<span class="ac3">CloudWatch Schedule</span>     ──┤\n<span class="ac3">Manual Trigger</span>          ──┘\n                           <span class="ac2">↓</span>\n                    <span class="ac1">AWS Lambda</span>        <span class="ac4">← Python handler, stateless</span>\n                           <span class="ac2">↓</span>\n                    <span class="ac1">Event Processing</span>  <span class="ac4">← business logic per event type</span>\n                           <span class="ac2">↓</span>\n     <span class="ac3">S3 Output</span>   <span class="ac3">CloudWatch Logs</span>   <span class="ac3">Downstream</span>\n\n<span class="ac4">  Infrastructure (Terraform)</span>\n  Lambda · S3 · IAM · CloudWatch → provisioned declaratively`,
      dec:'Terraform for IaC: the deployment environment is version-controlled, reproducible, and auditable. Manual console configuration creates undocumented drift between environments.',
      dec2:'Event-driven over polling loop: a polling loop pays for compute proportional to poll frequency regardless of event volume. Event-driven scales to zero when idle and handles burst traffic without pre-provisioning.',
      challenges:['Lambda cold start latency for infrequently invoked functions — acceptable here, would need provisioned concurrency for latency-sensitive cases.','Stateless execution required careful state management through S3 and CloudWatch rather than in-memory.'],
      testing:'Integration testing with real S3 upload events. CloudWatch log validation. Error case testing: malformed events, processing failures. Infrastructure reviewed via Terraform plan before apply.',
      lessons:'Infrastructure as Code is non-negotiable for cloud work. Destroying and recreating the entire pipeline from Terraform state in under 5 minutes made the value immediately obvious.',
      future:'Multi-region deployment · Dead letter queues for retry · Monitoring dashboards · Advanced alerting · Step Functions orchestration'}}
];

